            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rafi Amari is a product of the San Francisco that predates the latest tech boom. Born and raised in the Mission District, he is the only child of a Moroccan chef and a second-generation Filipina-American nurse. His childhood was a vibrant mix of cultures, flavors, and languages, played out against the backdrop of mural-covered alleyways. While he was never academically inclined, showing little interest in traditional schooling, Rafi discovered his passion early. He spent his teenage years with a cheap microphone and a cracked version of Pro Tools, meticulously recording local punk bands in his family\u2019s garage, obsessed with capturing the perfect, raw sound.\n\nAfter graduating high school, Rafi bypassed college, working a series of unfulfilling jobs\u2014barista, bike messenger, record store clerk\u2014while honing his audio engineering skills on the side. The turning point came with the podcasting explosion in the mid-2010s. He saw a new application for his talents beyond music. Starting as a freelance editor for independent creators, his keen ear for narrative pacing and clean audio quickly built his reputation. He eventually landed a full-time position as a producer, shaping stories for a popular tech and culture podcast based in SoMa.\n\nNow 38, Rafi lives a life of comfortable routine. He still resides in the Mission, fortunate to have a rent-controlled apartment a few blocks from his childhood home. His daily 1.8-mile commute on the J-Church MUNI is a time for listening and decompressing. Recently single after a long-term relationship ended over his refusal to leave the city, Rafi\u2019s connection to San Francisco has only deepened. His social life revolves around a tight-knit group of old friends and a few work colleagues, often meeting for beers at dive bars that have stubbornly resisted gentrification.\n\nHis professional success is gratifying, but Rafi dreams of more. He yearns to create his own narrative podcast series, one that chronicles the stories of the city\u2019s working-class immigrant families like his own\u2014the voices he feels are being drowned out. His aspiration is to use the skills he\u2019s perfected editing others\u2019 stories to finally tell the one that is truly his."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s nine years old, sitting on the kitchen floor while his father, Baba, cooks. The air is thick with cumin and coriander, but it\u2019s the sound that captivates him: the percussive chop of the knife, the hiss of onions in the tagine, and his mother\u2019s soft humming in Tagalog from the other room. He closes his eyes, trying to separate the layers. It\u2019s the first time he understands that sound isn\u2019t just noise, but a recipe. This moment planted the seed of his obsession with isolating and blending audio to create a feeling.\n\n2.\nHe\u2019s sixteen, crammed in the garage with the local punk trio, Static Bloom. After hours of failing, he finally captures the bassline so it thumps in your chest without swallowing the guitar's jagged edge. He plays back the 90-second track, and the scowling drummer\u2019s eyes go wide. \"That's it,\" the kid whispers. \"That's us.\" In that instant, Rafi felt a profound sense of purpose he never found in school. He wasn\u2019t just a technician; he was a translator for raw, fleeting emotion.\n\n3.\nAt twenty-seven, he\u2019s on the J-Church after a demoralizing record store shift, listening to an early narrative podcast. He hears the audio imperfections\u2014the clumsy edits, the uneven levels\u2014but below them, he hears the story. A switch flips in his mind. The same skills he used to capture a snarling vocal could be used to shape a person\u2019s narrative, to pace their words for emotional impact. The slow, rattling commute home suddenly felt less like an endpoint and more like the beginning of a new track.\n\n4.\nLast year, during the argument that ended it all. She stood by the window overlooking 20th Street, her bags packed. \"It\u2019s just a city, Rafi.\" He looked at the familiar orange glow from the taqueria, the distant rumble of the 14 Mission bus, and felt a pang of loss so sharp it was physical. He realized his roots in San Francisco weren't chains, but anchors. Choosing to stay wasn't an act of fear, but a solemn vow to the only home that had ever truly known him.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, sitting at a dive bar in the Excelsior, he overheard two old men arguing lovingly in Spanish about a soccer match from the 90s. Their voices, rich with history and belonging, were a sound he knew was fading from the city. He felt a sudden, urgent panic that these symphonies of everyday life were being erased. His vague dream of starting a podcast solidified into a mission. He had to capture these voices before the city\u2019s master track was remixed beyond recognition."
